{
  "answer": "In Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, the heaviest *saqi*-couplet—most desperate and intimate in its address—is the final *sher* of ghazal 198, where the poet beseeches the cupbearer amid utter desolation.[^1] Beyond pouring wine from a cup or flask, the *saqi* is asked to pour it directly from her own cupped hands (an act of reluctant physical closeness, even \"if you must hate\").\n\nIn Allama Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, the heaviest *saqi*-couplet—most prophetic and transformative—is the second *sher* of nazm 5, heralding a cosmic shift.[^2] Beyond pouring wine in secrecy, the *saqi* is invoked to embrace an unveiled era where the entire world becomes a tavern and every soul drinks openly.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/198-woh-aa-ke-khwaab-mein-taskeen-e-iztiraab-to-de/translation/#p-02279c).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/05-zamana-aaya-hai-be-hijabi-ka-aam-deedaar-e-yaar-ho/translation/#p-445c2f).",
